<h2 id="when-to-use">When to use tabbed navigation</h2>
<p>Use the tabbed navigation component when users need to move between related pages in a service.</p>
<p>It is designed for staff-facing services and most useful in services that staff use repeatedly.</p>

<h2 id="when-not-to-use">When not to use tabbed navigation</h2>
<p>Do not use tabbed navigation as the primary navigation in a service. Use the <a href="/design-system/components/header">header component</a> with the navigation option.</p>
<p>Do not use it on content-heavy public websites. Users may scroll past tabbed navigation on long content pages. To help users navigate content, consider the:</p>
<ul>
    <li><a href="/design-system/patterns/hub-page">hub page pattern</a></li>
    <li><a href="/design-system/patterns/mini-hub">mini hub pattern</a></li> 
</ul>
<p>Do not use it for links between sections of the same page. If you need to organise large amounts of content on a single page, consider:</p>
<ul>
    <li>cutting content back</li>
    <li>using headings</li>    
    <li>the <a href="/design-system/components/tabs">tab component</a></li>
    <li><a href="/design-system/components/expander">expanders</a></li>
    <li><a href="/design-system/components/details">details</a></li>
</ul>

<p>The tab component, expanders and details hide sections of content on a page which a user can choose to reveal. [Do we need to make it clearer what the differences between tab component and tabbed nav are here?]</p>
<p>Another form of secondary navigation is side navigation. If you would like to help us develop a side navigation component, get in touch or contribute via the side navigation GitHub issue in the design system backlog [create and link].</p>

<h2 id="how-to-use">How to use tabbed navigation</h2>
<p>Tabbed navigation looks like tabs but [note how it is different].</p>
<p>Unlike tabs, it does not use JavaScript. Each item in the navigation is a link to a separate page with a different URL. If you use the component for filtering a list or table, update the page's URL with a query string instead.</p>
<p>One of the items in tabbed navigation should always be highlighted as the current page. (This is different from the main navigation.) This item remains a link, but uses black text and has a line beneath it. [Amend if need be.]</p>
<p>On small screens, it displays vertically.</p>
<p>[Was there something about not displaying in a disabled state?]</p>
<h3>Positioning tabbed navigation on the page</h3>
<p>Put the component near the top of the page. Users may not see it if it is further down.</p>
<p>You can put it before or after the main heading (<code>h1</code>).</p>
<p>Users will probably expect any content above the tabbed navigation to display on the linked pages they navigate to.</p>
<p>The <code>h1</code> and the page title on each linked page should be unique. If you place the component below the main heading, there are several ways you can make each <code>h1</code> unique. For example, you can:</p>
<ul>
    <li>use hidden text</li>
    <li>use a caption</li>
</ul>
<p>[Explain and include examples?]</p>
